  id: Cervical_Vertebrae_C1_C7
  partName: Cervical Vertebrae
  descriptionChunks:
  - The cervical vertebrae are a series of seven bones forming the neck region of
    the canine vertebral column. These vertebrae support the head, protect the spinal
    cord, and allow extensive flexibility for movements such as bending, rotation,
    and extension.Specialized structures within the cervical vertebrae
  - provide attachment points for muscles and ligaments controlling head and neck
    motion. The first two vertebrae, the atlas and axis, enable a wide range of head
    mobility important for sensory awareness and balance. Proper alignment and health
    of the cervical spine are essential for posture and neurological function.
